    image: 'https://picsum.photos/id/1039/900/500', imageCredit: 'Weather Service',
    body: `<p>A powerful storm system is forecast to bring severe weather to a broad swath of the central United States this weekend, with the potential for tornadoes, large hail, and damaging straight-line winds.</p>
    <p>The Storm Prediction Center has issued an enhanced risk outlook for portions of Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas, and Missouri, warning that conditions will be favorable for significant severe weather from Saturday afternoon through early Sunday morning.</p>
    <p>"This is a classic spring severe weather setup," said senior forecaster Mike Collins. "We have warm, moist air surging northward from the Gulf, a strong jet stream overhead, and a potent cold front pushing east. The ingredients are all there."</p>
    <p>Emergency management agencies across the region are urging residents to review their severe weather plans and ensure they have multiple ways to receive warnings.</p>
    <p>The system is also expected to bring heavy rainfall of 2-4 inches across already saturated areas, raising the potential for flash flooding in low-lying and urban areas.</p>`
